Barack Obama to receive Nobel Peace Prize as fourth U.S. president
U.S. President Barack Obama will fly to Oslo, Norway, for 26 hours to claim the Nobel Peace Prize as the fourth U.S. president in history.
He will receive a diploma, a medal and a $1.4 million check, among other things, for his extraordinary efforts to strengthen world diplomacy and cooperation among nations.
The head of the White House will arrive in the Norwegian capital in the morning with his wife Michelle and will be busy.
First, he will visit the Nobel Institute, where he will meet for the first time with five members of the committee, which in October selected him from 172 people and 33 organizations.
The pair are scheduled to meet with King Harald V of Norway and Queen Sonja.
In the afternoon, the visit will culminate in a ceremonial ceremony, at which Obama will take on the prestigious award.
He will be the fourth President of the United States, but only the third to win the award in office.
The White House has already announced that Obama will be talking about the Afghan war when he receives the award.
The president does not want to avoid this topic, because he realizes that he is taking the prize as the president, who is currently at war in two countries.
The war effort a few days ago was further boosted by the deployment of more troops to Afghanistan, which will not be forgotten by any of his critics.
During the ceremony, Obama will also receive a gold medal, a diploma and a check for 10 million Swedish crowns (about 24 million Czech crowns).
He intends to donate to charity, but has not yet decided on a specific charity.
The packed program will then take the president and his wife to a banquet where, in addition to the Norwegian king and queen, the prime minister and 250 other invited guests will also be present.
From the start, Obama was more cautious about the price.
He said, for example, that he felt that he did not fully deserve it.
He also repeated several times that this is not just a price for him, but for all those who seek the same values as him.
Immediately after the announcement, he said it was a “call for action.”
