US: Repetition is the Mother of Wisdom
It is comical with what school effort Barack Obama, the president with the reputation of being the smartest, repeats in the Afghan question the strategy of his predecessor, who he himself considered to be the stupidest.
When he finally sweated out his eagerly awaited Afghan doctrine, it turned out that he wrote it through a copycat from the Bush Iraqi scenario three years ago.
Not only did he use the phrase “as in Iraq” several times in the text itself, but he did not hesitate to even use the title of Bush’s January 2007 statement as the title of his own declaration: “A New Way Forward.”
Three years ago, he criticised Bush’s idea of sending fresh military reinforcements to a civil war-torn Iraq as “irresponsible and catastrophic in its consequences.”
However, the months that followed showed that Bush’s strategy, based on the recommendations of the field commanders, was the only possible and highly successful one, so much so that there is no mention of Iraq in the news reports today.
It did not improve Bush’s reputation, but objectively left his successor with a much more grateful starting situation than could have been expected.
In Afghanistan, Barack Obama hopes that the miracle will happen again.
He was again asked to increase the military contingent by field commanders, especially the commander-in-chief of the Afghan operation, General Stanley McCristal, who, even in spite of subordinationist practices, harshly criticized the hesitant shooters in the White House.
He asked 40,000 men to break the situation for the better.
The president hesitated for three months, but he didn't think of anything better, so at least he cheated the general by 10,000 troops.
From Europe he managed to squeeze out the promise of another 5,000, although he initially counted himself at least 10.
The most problematic part of Obama’s entire strategy seems to be his intention to start withdrawing troops from Afghanistan in 18 months and to end the process in three years.
Many doubt that a half-increase will produce the same fruit as the process in Iraq.
Despite the fratricidal wars of recent years, the Iraqi society is relatively well-ordered, its leaders honoring the agreements.
The Afghan situation is characterized by the opposite symptom - no one can be trusted and no agreements are respected.
Under these conditions, Afghan security forces are ill-prepared to change their master every day as they see fit.
Political institutions, even if formally established, will remain only a potemkin village, behind which patriarchal tribal relations will continue to flourish.
Balancing the interests of different ethnic groups is extremely difficult due to the lack of clarity of the situation, which is further complicated by Pakistani and Iranian influences.
Even the construction of an “accessible state”, which is the minimalist goal of the entire operation, does not seem too real.
The time horizon of Obama’s strategy is striking with its voluntarism.
Over the past eight years, the situation in Afghanistan has only worsened and is now on the verge of explosion.
To believe that soldiers sent into the war to “return home quickly” will cause a miracle here, can only be a truly romantic soul, untouched by reality.
From a political point of view, setting a date for the withdrawal of troops is purely irresponsible, as the Taliban will see it as an indirect admission of American defeat.
The latest NATO summit showed that the willingness of Europeans to take part in combat operations in Afghanistan is approaching a minus.
European politicians do not know and do not want to explain to their voters how the security of Germany or Italy is related to the war in the foothills of the Hindu Kush.
Another factor capable of radically intervening in the situation is the development of events around Iran.
If the situation continues to deteriorate and the increased sanctions do not affect the Iranians, the United States will be faced with an overly difficult question of whether to try to solve the problem by military force.
It will be necessary to answer it just at the time when, according to Obama, America will proceed to a victorious withdrawal from Afghanistan.
However, any such solution will also mean a dramatic turnaround in the Afghan situation.
The only patch for Barack Obama is the fact that there are three years left before the presidential election, and therefore there is still enough time for him to come up with another strategy if it turns out to be a total failure.
