Incomplete suppression of the multiplication of the virus also results in the development of so-called resistant viruses, against which drugs are already ineffective.
The work of experts from three institutes of the Academy of Sciences of the Czech Republic, from the University of Life Sciences Prague and from the University of Heidelberg opens a way to deal with the resistance of the virus.
They have shown that a substance called metallocarbons acts on the protein responsible for the multiplication of HIV.
Metalocarbons are compounds of boron, hydrogen, carbon and cobalt.
These compounds block the spread of the virus differently than all the drugs used today, and therefore can overcome the problem of resistance.
In their work, scientists come up with new ‘improved’ compounds prepared on the basis of knowledge of the molecular mechanism of their binding to the viral protein.
Metal carbonates have a unique three-dimensional structure: two multi-walled cages made up of boron, hydrogen and carbon atoms are connected by a metal atom, in this case cobalt.
Betrayal and Resistant Virus
HIV protease is a protein of the HIV virus that is necessary for the life cycle of the virus.
Without HIV protease caused by HIV cleavage, no mature infectious virus particles would have formed.
If we stop HIV protease, we will also stop the spread of the virus in the patient’s body, scientists explain in a press release published by the Institute of Organic Chemistry and Biochemistry of the Academy of Sciences of the Czech Republic.
In a paper published in the Journal of Medical Chemistry, scientists describe a series of compounds in which two pairs of cages (see table) are connected by a short organic chain, which is further systematically modified.
A little weaker, but more reliable
The effect of this series of HIV protease agents was tested in the test tube and also against its resistant (resistant) variants derived from patients infected with HIV.
The effect of metal carbonates on a common variant of the enzyme is not as strong as that of clinically used drugs, but it does not lose its effect for resistant variants against which the drugs used are often ineffective.
The unique mechanism of action, as well as their other properties such as biological and chemical stability, low toxicity and the possibility of further chemical modifications make metalocarbonates interesting compounds for further research aimed at the design of effective drugs against HIV, says Pavl<0xC3><0xAD>na <0xC5><0x98>ez<0xC3><0xA1><0xC4><0x8D>ov<0xC3><0xA1>, head of the Laboratory of Structural Biology at the Institute of Biochemistry and the Institute of Organic Biology.
