Wang Weijia and her husband grew up surrounded by propaganda posters reading that "Mother Earth is too exhausted to feed more children" and "One extra child means one extra grave".
Then they learned that when official government posts in Shanghai, alarmed by the low birth rates and ageing population in their city, suddenly changed course this summer and began encouraging young couples, their response was immediate and determined: Never.
We have always devoted all our time and energy to just one child.
We didn’t keep anything for anyone else, says Wang, 31, a human resource manager who has an 8-month-old son.
China’s more than 30-year-old policy of having only one child has been put in place, creating two generations of only notoriously chubby and spoiled children, affectionately called “little emperors,” who are threatened by a population crisis.
The average birth rate fell to 1.8 children per couple compared to six before the policy came into force, according to UN data.
The distribution of the population, where the population aged 60 years and above is projected to rise turbulently from 16.7 percent of the population in 2020 to 31.1 percent in 2050. This is well above the overall average of about 20 percent.
The imbalance is greater in affluent coastal cities with populations with higher education, for example in Shanghai.
Last year, people aged 60 and older accounted for almost 22 percent of Shanghai’s registered population, while the birth rate was less than one child per couple.
Xie Lingli, director of the Shanghai City Commission for Population and Family Planning, said many couples must have children to “help reduce the proportions of an aging population and reduce the number of workers in the future.”
He says it's about "being old doesn't mean being rich -- like in developed countries like Japan or Sweden."
Gradually calming
As enshrined in the country’s constitution in 1978, China’s one-child policy is probably still the most controversial mandate introduced under the Communist Party.
Couples who violated politics faced huge fines -- up to three times their annual salary in some areas -- and discrimination at work.
China’s official offices have promoted policies that have helped the country prevent critical exploitation of natural resources, while human rights defenders have been condemned for pursuing policies.
In rural areas, some officials forced pregnant women to undergo abortions with their second child.
In addition, many couples had to undergo sex-selective abortions, leading to an unnaturally high ratio of men to women.
In recent years, population officials have been gradually milder in their stance on the one-child policy.
In 2004, they generally allowed exceptions - including city dwellers, members of national minorities, and cases where men and women were singles - and in 2007, they eased the dictation of their hardline slogans.
Qiao Xiaochun, a professor at the Beijing University Institute of Population Research, said central government officials had previously debated more radical changes, such as allowing couples to have two children if one of the partners was a single child.
In June, Shanghai became the first Chinese city to launch an aggressive campaign to encourage more births.
Almost overnight, posters urging parents to have only one child were replaced with copies of the decree detailing how it would be justified to have a second child and how to apply for permission.
The city administration sent family planning officials and volunteers to meet couples in their homes and slip leaflets under the door.
They also promised to provide emotional and financial advice to those who chose to have more than one child.
The reaction was cold, family planning officials said.
Disturbing Reaction
While officials in one rural city near Shanghai have seen an increase in interest among couples who would like to have a second child after the campaign starts, most city districts have not reported changes.
The city district of Huinan with a population of 115000, for example, still registered four to five cases per month.
Disappointed officials in Shanghai said that despite the campaign, the number of births in the city in 2010 is still expected to be only around 165,000 - slightly higher than in 2009, but lower than in 2008.
Feng Juying, head of the family planning committee in Shanghai’s Caol district, said financial considerations were probably the main reason people didn’t want to have more children.
They want to give the best to the first child, he said.
Yang Jiawei, 27, and his wife, Liu Juanjan, 26, said she would like to have two children and they were legally allowed to do so.
But like many Chinese, who only have insufficient health and life insurance, provided by the government.
Without a backup network, the choice could be irresponsible.
People in the West misjudge the one-child policy as a controversial legal issue, says Yang, a construction engineer whose wife is in union with her first child at the seventh month of pregnancy.
Yes, we were impoverished by the chance to have more than one child.
But the problem is not only in politics.
It's about money.
Other couples cite psychological reasons for hesitation.
Wang, a human resource manager, says they only want one child because she was also an only child: “We were the center of attention of our families and everyone was taking care of us.
We weren’t used to provide care and in fact we didn’t want to take care of others.
Chen Zijian, 42, who owns a translation company, expressed this much more unobtrusively.
For middle-class two-career parents who have reduced birth rates, he said, being successful means being selfish.
Today’s 20- and 30-year-olds view parents as breaking through the first days of China’s experiment with capitalism, and they don’t want this way of living for themselves, he says.
