The Managerial Revolution or the End of Economic Intelligence?
If nothing changes in the management of the great French companies, our struggle for the development of economic intelligence was useless...
For more than a decade, the behavior of the management of large companies towards employees has been reminiscent of the attitude of companies towards consumers before the marketing revolution: it is about identifying employees with "values" determined from the mountain, as it was before, when it was necessary to impose on the consumer products that came from the ideas of the heads of factory technicians.
By making the customer the center of the business, the marketing revolution has compared the strategy of conquering the market in the right direction...even though authoritarian efforts to impose products other than customer preferences are regularly returning!
Passive attitudes of employees can lead to fatal demoralization.
Suicides at France Telecom, PSA or Renault are just a visible part of a much more widespread general phenomenon that affects mostly management cadres.
This demobilization adversely affects the development of all intellectual functions of society, including research and development, and more importantly, economic intelligence.
Indeed, the EI "requires from all stakeholders (...) an active approach and the ability to anticipate" and requires from employees commitments that are completely contrary to the revenues of authoritarian management.
