The Turkish justice system has dissolved for the Kurdish side and this decision has serious consequences.
Turkey's Constitutional Court on Friday ruled to dismantle the country's main pro-Kurdish party, prompting protests in the Kurdish community in the country's southeast and in Istanbul.
This decision can greatly complicate the task of the government, which is trying to give the Kurdish community a friendly hand and thus try to end 25 years of conflict.
The Democratic Society Party (DTP) was dissolved because it has become "a nest of activities threatening the independence of the state and its indivisible unity," Supreme Court President Hasim Kilic told reporters after four days of negotiations.
The decision was taken unanimously by 11 judges, when a majority of seven votes were needed to dissolve the party, Kili<0xC3><0xA7> said, adding that 37 party cadres, including its president Ahmet Türk and MP Aysely Tuglukov<0xC3><0xA1>, were banned from participating in political life for five years.
