The DTP party has 21 seats in Parliament (out of 500).
The party's leadership warned ahead of the verdict that MPs would rather leave Parliament than act as MPs without political affiliation.
The decision is a continuation of the trial initiated in 2007 by the Prosecutor of the Court of Cassation Abdurrahman Yalcinkay, who accuses the DTP of obeying the "orders" of the Kurdistan Workers' Party (PKK), which Ankara and many countries consider a terrorist organization.
Many observers believe that the DTP is the legal political showcase of the PKK rebels.
The party assures that it has no "essential link" with the PKK, but refuses to label it a terrorist organization and calls on the government to negotiate with it.
The verdict comes as the government gives the Kurdish community a friendly hand and offers a range of measures to strengthen their rights, seeking to curb Kurdish support for the PKK and end the conflict.
The DTP leadership confirmed that the dissolution of the party could lead to renewed tensions in southeastern Anatolia, where many demonstrations against the conditions under which PKK leader Abdullah Öcalan is detained in clashes with police have broken up in recent weeks.
Since the announcement of the ruling, thousands of demonstrators have gathered outside the DTP headquarters in Diyarbakir, a large city in the southeast inhabited mostly by Kurds.
Police used tear gas grenades and water cannons, and demonstrators threw Molotov cocktails or shot rocks from slingshots.
About a hundred people also demonstrated in Istanbul.
After the verdict was handed down, Mr Türk said the justice decision would only "deepen despair".
Turkey cannot solve this issue by banning the party, he said in the press.
The government, made up of a party from the Islamist movement, also condemned the decision.
We are, on principle, against interference.
It does not solve anything, Energy Minister Taner Yildiz said.
