The cradle of dinosaurs
Tawa hallae looked like a lot of other carnivorous dinosaurs: The animal, two meters long and 1.50 meters high, ran on two strong hind limbs, had an elongated skull with sharp, curved teeth, short front limbs with sickle claws and a long tail.
If this species had lived a few million years later, it would not have been extraordinary.
Sterling Nesbitt of the University of Texas at Austin and colleagues in the Thursday issue of the journal Science write that Tawa hallae, however, was one of the first dinosaurs with these bodily features.
The animal lived about 215 million years ago in what is now New Mexico, which was then located in the equatorial dry region of the supercontinent Pangea.
Tawa opens a new window to the earlier evolution of dinosaurs, says Nesbitt.
It shows us a lot about kinship relationships, expansions and signs of early dinosaurs.
In 2006, Nesbitt and other palaeontologists began excavating at the Ghost Ranch in northern New Mexico.
Sometimes in one day we found a dozen dinosaur bones, which is unprecedented for triassic deposits, according to team member Randall Irmis of the Museum of Natural History in Utah.
Some of the bones were quickly identified by scientists as a new species.
During the excavations, they collected the remains of a total of five individuals.
The finding confirms theories about the early history of dinosaurs.
The name "Tawa" comes from the sun god of the Hopi Indians.
For Sterling Nesbitt, this is an unusual finding: "The fossils of dinosaurs from the Triassic are very rare, usually only individual fragments are found."
Other dinosaur experts do not share this enthusiasm without reservation.
This finding is not particularly sensational, but confirms some theories about the early history of dinosaurs, says Martin Sander from the University of Bonn.
According to the current scientific opinion, dinosaurs first appeared about 230 million years ago.
However, many of the oldest fossils are not complete, so the assignment of pradinosaurs is mostly controversial.
Experts discuss, for example, when lizards split into the three most important developmental lines: carnivorous theropods, which later included Tyrannosaurus rex, Velociraptor and also birds, "long-necked" four-legged sauropods and their relatives, and herbivores, ornithipts.
Tawa hallae is the original terapod after analysis by Nesbitt and his colleagues.
It exhibits an interesting combination of primitive and advanced properties, says Nesbitt.
On the skull of Tawa hallae, for example, researchers found evidence of air bags that even the descendants of theropods have birds.
Thanks to air bags, the breathing of birds is more effective than that of mammals.
At Tawa hallae, the bones of the spine were apparently partly filled with air.
Tawa is the oldest and most primitive theropod with air bags, says Randall Irmis.
Since a related line of giant sauropods later also had air bags and light bones, he created this useful innovation, probably a common ancestor of both groups.
At least three waves of migration to North America
Since the most primitive dinosaurs known to date lived in South America, scientists have deduced that lizards first appeared there.
According to this, the three lines of development soon split and spread from South America to all the continents, which at that time, as a supercontinent of Pangea, formed a single earth mass.
The fact that the team and Tawa hallae found the remains of two other, not particularly closely related, theropods would also speak for it.
The three cannot come from a single common, immigrant ancestor, the researchers argue.
We believe there have been at least three migration waves to North America, says Alan Turner of the American Museum of Natural History in New York, co-author of the study.
Of course, there are also contradictions.
An even older species, Silesaurus, which belongs to the group of the heaviest dinosaurs, lived in present-day Poland, says Bonn paleontologist Martin Sander.
His hypothesis could put together a distorted picture, because in South America very many primitive dinosaur fossils have been preserved, with other continents seldom found.
How dinosaurs proved that they evolved from a relatively rare by-line of the reptile genus to the ruling vertebrates on earth during the Earth's Middle Ages remains a puzzle.
During the Triassic, dinosaurs shared their habitat with many other reptiles, such as the ancestors of today’s crocodiles and flying lizards, and countless other lizards.
Around the end of the Triassic, dinosaurs spread across the world and many new species developed, while relatives died out and the Triassic and Jurassic interfaces.
The success story didn’t last forever.
There are two hypotheses to explain this change, says Martin Sander.
There could have been a mass extinction, which dinosaurs accidentally survived, but reptiles did not.
Or the dinosaurs adapted better so they could push out the competition.
The success story didn’t last forever.
150 million years later, the impact of a meteorite helped another group of animals, which also evolved in the Triassic and has lived in the shadows ever since: mammals.
