Some see images in the waking state and hear voices that others do not see and hear.
It is not only the mentally ill or drug addicts who cross the line between imagination and reality.
As long as it happens in your sleep, everything is fine.
If we lie with our eyes closed in our dark room, we can surround ourselves with the wildest fantasies and fantasy delusions.
But he who experiences dream states in vigilance, sees and hears things that others do not see and hear, in today’s Western world he is usually considered a fool or a drug addict, or at least a freak.
However, such images and voices do not arise only in the mentally ill or in drug intoxication.
The same neuronal processes that allow us to design houses, paint paintings, or write novels will make sure that the boundaries between dream, imagination, and reality merge.
Dreams altered state of consciousness can occur in various forms, at best we call them visions, in worse delusions.
Although the initiator and the effect may differ, the visions of the mystic Hildegard von Bingen, the drug experiences of the New-Age prophet Carlos Castaneda, shamanic states of delusion, psychosis and hallucinations can be deduced from similar processes.
Hallucinations or visions occur when the balance of neuronal transmitters of the brain - mainly dopamine, norepinephrine, serotonin and acetylcholine - is deflected and interactions between different parts of the brain are disrupted.
Complex hallucinations and delusions occur very often in schizophrenic psychosis.
Gravity has no power over it.
The connection between delusion and dream has employed philosophers and physicians since antiquity.
Aristoteles understood hallucinations as a form of dreaming in a waking state, Wilhelm Griesinger, one of the founders of modern psychology, stated in 1861 "the great similarity of delusions to dream states", for Sigmund Freud the dream was even "psychosis, with all nonsense, delusions, delusions of the senses".
