Scientists believe that the affected person has minimal brain damage.
We believe that at an early stage of development there will be damage to the neural maturation of the brain, for example, viral diseases of the mother during pregnancy, explains Fuchs.
However, it remains a puzzle as to how the neuronal system will break down, which has not manifested itself in any way for many years.
The influences of the environment also play a role - stress or traumatic experiences can be the initiator of psychosis, if there is a disposition to it.
Also, hallucinogenic drugs can trigger psychosis because they interfere with the transmission system.
When our brains shut down
It’s crazy that psychotronics suffer from their hallucinations, and to get rid of them, they swallow expensive medications, others give money for drugs to get them, says psychology professor Erich Kasten of Lübeck.
Whether we perceive delusions as pleasant or unpleasant is often just a matter of attitude.
Kasten has been collecting reports of hallucinations and delusions for ten years, and last year he interpreted his results in the book "Die irreal Welt in unserm Kopf" (The Unreal World in Our Head).
Hallucinations are a typical accompanying phenomenon of psychosis, but also surprisingly many other diseases.
In addition to mental disorders such as borderline personality or depression, also often diseases such as migraine, epilepsy, multiple sclerosis or Alzheimer's or brain trauma.
Surprisingly, the brain of a healthy person also hallucinates under certain conditions.
Hallucinations, according to Kasten, consist of the contents of thoughts that are normally suppressed.
They arise when the parts of the brain in which sensory perception is processed are too active or under-repressed; when our brains become clogged, or when stimulation is lacking.
Drugs can trigger this condition as well as brain damage or psychosis.
But also the withdrawal of stimuli, stress, worries about love or other exceptional conditions.
In recent studies, up to a third of those surveyed said they had experienced hallucinations at least once in their lives.
In the summer of 2005, Sarah K. is 16 years old, lives in a small town in Mecklenburg-Vorpommern and attends the gymnasium there.
In fact, a completely normal girl.
If it weren't for the shapes and the voices.
At breaks, she may be approached by a cologne with long, dark hair.
When she answers, her classmates look at her with surprise - no one but her sees and hears this boy.
This shy girl thinks she's a tense dreamer, but Sarah K. doesn't dream, she knows.
He is awake, he hears and sees the boy, just as he hears and sees the girl sitting next to him in the bench.
He can even feel his presence, at least for a few moments.
It's a nice feeling, she likes the boy.
Am I crazy? he asks sometimes.
But he knows that this boy and other delusions are not real and will disappear again.
At night, the sights are rather depressing.
Frequently, delusions are a burden.
When she sits in a classroom, she cannot watch the lessons many times, because the teacher in her eyes and ears is just presenting a new classmate, while he explains to everyone else audiblely and visibly on the table of mathematical equations.
At night, the apparitions are rather depressing.
When she waits in her dark room to sleep, which comes in seldom and too late, she cannot often tell whether she is awake or asleep, whether the images she sees, the grimaces, or the girl with the bleeding cuts on her arms and legs appear in front of her open or closed eyes.
Leave me alone, he's yelling at the characters.
She doesn't tell her parents and friends about it, they'd think she was crazy.
Autumn 2009. Sarah K. is 20 years old today.
She graduated last year and lives with her boyfriend.
A year ago, the hallucinations stopped.
Ever since she contacted psychologist Kasten on the Internet, she knows exactly that she hasn't gone crazy.
Delusions are also the art of despair.
If someone is socially isolated or is stripped of their stimulus, they are likely to have hallucinations, Kasten says.
I think the brain doesn’t have enough jobs and takes care of its own entertainment.
Sarah K., an only child, was afraid of other children as a little girl, often playing alone.
Her hallucinations began when she learned at the age of 13 that a man she had called her father since she had thought was not her own father.
Because visual and acoustic hallucinations involve the same brain regions that process real perceptions and sounds, it’s hard for people like Sarah K. to distinguish between delusions and reality.
Hallucinations are also images that let the brain form, which is why it seems so real.”
Also, the night dreams evaluate Kasten as a form of hallucination.
Hallucinations of healthy people are not fundamentally different from hallucinations in acute psychosis.
Unlike schizophrenics, mentally healthy people are able to identify their delusions as unrealistic.
Kasten therefore advises his patients to evaluate hallucinations as an extraordinary ability.
The borderline state between dreaming and hallucination
Unfortunately, in our world that is too concentrated, the imaginary experience is mostly pathologized, says Michael Schmidt-Degenhard, professor in Heidelberg and chief physician at the Psychiatry and Psychotherapy Clinic at the Florence-Nightingale Hospital in Düsseldorf.
Psychosis is a severe, painful disease, but it also brings positives, creativity - a delusion is also an art of despair.
Schmidt-Degenhard explored the so-called oneiroid form of experience, a peculiar form of altered consciousness toward sleep.
Oneiroid states are highly complex, detailed, fictitious dreams that the affected person considers to be real and cannot even retroactively distinguish them from the waking state.
Oneiroid state of consciousness arises in extreme situations caused by trauma or disease, for example, patients with polyradicular inflammation who experience motor paralysis in full consciousness.
When a person is threatened by the loss of the world and himself, for example, by a permanent, complete inability to move, he replaces the life-threatening real situation with his own, imaginary world, which is disconnected from reality, says Schmidt-Degenhard.
A kind of borderline state between dreaming and hallucination.
Because it is impossible to manage a situation in reality, there will be a change in the worlds, but the real situation will become present in the imagination.
An intense form of sensory support and sensory transfer in some unbearable situation that allows people to have their own ability to form in an instant into a loss of consciousness.
Everything is real, even later in the memories
Also, art historian Peter Cornelius Claussen describes his oneiroid experiences in his book "Herzwechsel" (The Exchange of Hearts) as a saving action of the soul.
He was 49 years old when, after heart valve surgery and subsequent heart transplant, his consciousness set out on a multi-day journey, with his body lying motionless in an intensive care unit.
Claussen immersed himself in the world he created, visited strange times and places: he becomes an old man tied to a bed, in a train sanatorium, a robot guards his health.
He lives in the early Middle Ages among the nobility, which produces narcotics from blood.
A Greek kidnaps him on a motorcycle to his homeland, surfing the Firna in the Alps on a hospital bed, and encounters a Korean mobster.
It is completely immersed in imaginary events, everything is real, even later in memories.
These inner paths for Claussen are fundamentally different from any dream.
A dream is a different state, it describes its experience.
In contrast to dreams, the memories of these mental paths are still clear after years and in insignificant details.
Even brighter and more intense than the real experience.
The intensity of this experience breaks the horizon of our other true experiences, says psychiatrist Schmidt-Degenhard.
After all, oneiroid states, psychoses, hallucinations, and drug intoxication show how fragile even in the waking state our inner images of external reality are.
Any change in the state of consciousness, summarizes psychologist Kasten, "can lead to a deformation of what we call reality."
A reality that can also be enriching.
