In fact, they are already part of the mandatory equipment of all newly registered passenger cars and light commercial vehicles, while others have a deadline for eliminating the shortage, which is February 2011.
The measure introduced in the EU aims to increase pedestrian protection, working in such a way that it can help to avoid many collisions.
The handbrake assist system increases the pressure on the brakes in an emergency, which the system detects when the driver steps down.
But it is not always possible to maintain this pressure until the end.
According to a study carried out by auto parts manufacturer Bosch, a third of the drivers in an accident did not step the brake before the collision, and half of them did not make full use of the brake power.
Up to 1,100 accidents
On the contrary, this assistance requires maximum from the braking system, shortening the braking distance of the vehicle.
According to a study carried out in the EU itself, if all vehicles were equipped with this type of equipment, up to 1,100 pedestrian-related deaths could be prevented per year.
Reducing this number will be even more significant—according to calculations, one in four accidents with an impact on persons would be prevented—after the introduction of so-called intelligent handbrake systems.
In this case, the vehicles will be equipped with a system that (via radar or camera) captures obstacles and reports them to the driver, except for light braking.
If the driver reacts, it will help him to increase the pressure on the pedal, if necessary.
If the driver does not react, even if a collision cannot be prevented, the device will hit the brakes as intensely as possible and reduce the risk of damage to a minimum.
